Adelani Adepegba, Abuja The Nigerian Air Force has said it will deploy Unmanned Aerial Vehicles, popularly known as drones, to deal with bandits and insurgents in the North-West and North-East regions. It added that the drones would be stationed in Katsina and Gusau to cover the North-West and Gombe for the North-East. According to a statement in Abuja on Saturday by the NAF spokesman, Air Commodore, Ibikunle Daramola, the Chief of the Air Staff, Air Marshal Sadique Abubakar, disclosed this while celebrating Eid-el-Kabir with frontline troops in Katsina, where he commended the men for their sacrifices. Daramola said the CAS warned the bandits to lay down their arms and surrender to appropriate authorities or face the consequences. The statement read in part, “The CAS equally revealed that some of the Unmanned Aerial Vehicles being procured for the NAF would be stationed in Katsina and Gusau, to cover the North-West and Gombe for the North-East. “He stated that steps were also being taken to improve the development and employment of NAF Special Forces in order to keep them motivated to remain the excellent lethal force they had become.” The Katsina State Governor, Aminu Masari, saluted the NAF operatives for their efforts in combating banditry and insurgency in the region. Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com 